licate the `ObjectImporter` class. But using dynamic loading with Native Image could cause issues, so I'll handle errors accordingly and ensure I’m not using reflection directly where possible.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Clarifying class loading for tests**\\n\\nFor my test, the goal is to initialize the class. I can define class bytes from a jar resource within a custom `ClassLoader`, and I might need to define a Proxy. The `ObjectImporter` class implements Serializable and uses only JDK in its static initialization. I need to ensure I'm using a child-first loader since Class.forName won’t return the existing class if I use parent-first. It's also important to catch any potential errors that arise during this process. The complexity lies in dynamic access with Class.forName, and I need to consider how loaders interact with class loading and initialization.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Assessing dynamic class loading challenges**\\n\\nI’m considering whether my agent instruments Class.forName calls in loaded classes. It seems likely, especially if I include a user filter for `javassist.**`. However, in Native Image, I can't define a duplicate class at runtime, so I really need to catch any unsupported errors that arise. If I include a test for defining the duplicate class, it’s important to catch errors and verify Native Image support. I also have to ensure that the class bytes for the `ObjectImporter` resource aren't unintentionally transformed when referencing its initialization.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating class initialization**\\n\\nI'm considering how the one-argument Class.forName initializes with the caller loader. If a class is currently being initialized, it returns that class instead of redefining it. I'm wondering if Class.forName in a test might duplicate this initialization.\\n\\nNow, in a native image scenario, defining the ObjectImporter from bytes brings up concerns about dynamic class loading. 